    "body": "## Goal\n\nMake Verdikta's criteria-based judgment and settlement system demonstrably fair, auditable, resistant to adversarial inputs, and accurately described to users and partners.\n\n## Context\n\nA Miroshark simulation identified the likely next wave of public and partner scrutiny: legal framing, model disagreement, prompt gaming, and the tradeoff between auditability and exposing defense mechanisms.\n\nThe work is intentionally consolidated into a small number of dependency-aware deliverables spanning protocol mechanics, applications, arbiters, shared standards, documentation, public positioning, and prediction-market pilots.\n\nCore framing:\n\n> Verdikta is a judgment and settlement layer for criteria-based outcomes.\n\n> Automated by default, configurable by risk.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Evergreen public materials use accurate criteria-based judgment and settlement language and qualified cost/performance claims.\n- [ ] Ambiguous, divergent, and near-threshold evaluations have explicit bounded resolution paths.\n- [ ] A versioned Verdict Packet standard makes decisions and settlement evidence legible without exposing every adversarial defense.\n- [ ] Reliability metrics, rubric preflight, templates, and adversarial-evaluation controls are available and validated.\n- [ ] Legal and usage guardrails distinguish protocol settlement signals from courts or regulated arbitration.\n- [ ] Trust content, red-team activity, and prediction-market shadow pilots are backed by implemented behavior and evidence.\n\n## Validation\n\nReview every child issue's completion evidence, then run representative bounty and shadow-resolution cases covering fast consensus, disagreement, near-threshold escalation, inconclusive handling, challenge behavior, Verdict Packet inspection, rubric linting, and prompt-injection defenses.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn scope:\n\n- Public positioning and legal/usage guardrails\n- Adaptive consensus and bounded challenges\n- Verdict Packet standard and explorer\n- Reliability metrics\n- Rubric preflight and templates\n- Adversarial evaluation and public trust work\n- Prediction-market shadow pilots\n\nOut of scope:\n\n- Claims that Verdikta replaces courts, lawyers, or regulated arbitration\n- Unbounded appeals or creator vetoes\n- Publishing secret prompts or anti-gaming mechanisms in real time\n- Calendar-based launch commitments",
