    "body": "## Goal\n\nEnable Verdikta bounty escrow and settlement in a deliberately small allowlist of approved ERC-20 tokens, beginning with native USDC on Base, without accepting arbitrary token contracts.\n\n## Context\n\nVerdikta's bounty escrow currently uses ETH. Stablecoin-denominated bounties can make reward values easier to understand and fund, but general ERC-20 support would expose the system to malicious or nonstandard token behavior.\n\nThe approved default is an owner- or multisig-controlled on-chain allowlist with explicit events. The first supported token is native USDC on Base. Fee-on-transfer, rebasing, callback-bearing, and otherwise nonstandard tokens are excluded.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] The escrow contract safely supports native USDC on Base through an explicit allowlist.\n- [ ] Arbitrary token addresses and unsupported token behaviors are rejected.\n- [ ] Bounty APIs, user interfaces, indexing, agent workflows, and documentation represent token amounts and addresses correctly.\n- [ ] Existing ETH bounty behavior remains compatible and covered by regression tests.\n- [ ] Deployment, migration, monitoring, and emergency-control procedures are documented and validated.\n\n## Validation\n\nComplete contract and application test suites, deploy to the intended staging network, and execute end-to-end ETH and USDC bounty lifecycles covering creation, submission, evaluation, settlement, refunds, and rejection of unsupported tokens.\n\n## Scope\n\nIn scope:\n\n- Native USDC on Base as the first allowlisted ERC-20\n- Explicit allowlist administration and events\n- Contract, application, agent, and documentation support\n- Security tests and operational validation\n\nOut of scope:\n\n- Permissionless arbitrary ERC-20 support\n- Fee-on-transfer, rebasing, ERC-777-style callback, or other nonstandard token behavior\n- Support for every chain or stablecoin",
